##############################################
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-95-The expression parser of math.js has support for letting functions
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md:96:parse and evaluate arguments themselves, instead of calling them with
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md:97:evaluated arguments. This is useful for example when creating a function
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-98-like `plot(f(x), x)` or `integrate(f(x), x, start, end)`, where some of the
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-99-arguments need to be processed in a special way. In these cases, the expression
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md:100:`f(x)` will be evaluated repeatedly by the function, and `x` is not evaluated
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-101-but used to specify the variable looping over the function `f(x)`.
##############################################
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-103-Functions having a property `rawArgs` with value `true` are treated in a special
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md:104:way by the expression parser: they will be invoked with unevaluated arguments,
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-105-allowing the function to process the arguments in a customized way. Raw
##############################################

/src/docs/expressions/customization.md:116:- `scope` is the scope provided when evaluating the expression.

##############################################
/src/docs/expressions/customization.md-119-processed at compile time. They are not supported when passed via a scope

/src/docs/expressions/parsing.md:1:# Expression parsing and evaluation
/src/docs/expressions/parsing.md-2-
/src/docs/expressions/parsing.md:3:Expressions can be parsed and evaluated in various ways:
